ninkrijk"},"en":{"1130–1219":"1130–1219","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1170–1219":"1170–1219","1174–Female":"1174–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","about 1219":"about 1219","1215":"1215","about 1205":"about 1205","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","about 1165":"about 1165","1219":"1219","1170":"1170","Dover Castle, Kent, England":"Dover Castle, Kent, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","North Petherton, Somerset, England":"North Petherton, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wrotham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Middlesex): habitational name from Wortham in Suffolk, named with Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"william","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":85,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"william de Wrotham was born in 1130, in North Petherton, Somerset, England. He married Maud de Cornhall about 1205, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1219, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1130–1219":"1130–1219","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1170–1219":"1170–1219","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","about 1219":"umbes 1219","1215":"1215","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1219":"1219","1170":"1170","Dover Castle, Kent, England":"Dover Castle, Kent, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Petherton, Somerset, England":"North Petherton, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1130–1219":"1130–1219","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1170–1219":"1170–1219","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170",